In [[Marsember]], [[Cormyr]], wooden [[skiff]]s were treated with fish oil or tar to seal hull imperfections during the building process. In a similar manner, a bright red mix of fish oil and certain local roots was used to treat ships' oar sockets on the isle of [[Oman]] in the [[Moonshae Isles]].

In alchemy, fish oil was one of the ingredients in brewing ''[[potion of power|potions of power]]'', ''[[potion of defense|potions of defense]]'', ''[[potion of deflect|potions of deflection]]'', ''[[potion of critical strike|potions of critical strike ]]'', ''[[flask of potency|flasks of potency]]'', and especially potent versions of ''[[potion of fortification]]'', ''[[potion of accuracy]]'', ''[[potion of force]]'', ''[[potion of reflexes]]'', and ''[[tidespan potion]]''.

In blacksmithing, fish oil was used to treat forged items like [[dagger|knives]], [[scythe]]s, [[axe|hatchet]]s, [[hammer]]s, and swordbreaker [[sword]]s.

[[Sahuagin]] priestesses of the shark god [[Sekolah]] used fish blubber, fish oil, and certain sea chemicals to make incendiary weapons called ''[[Sekolah's fire]]'', mixed with air, and packed into tubes. The recipe for this dangerous jelly was a secret only known to the High Priestesses of Sekolah.{{Cite dragon/239/Sneaky Sea Devils|11}}

[[Maerlus|Maerlus the Magnificent]] of [[Waterdeep]]'s [[Watchful Order of Magists and Protectors]] claimed that fish oil was useful for romancing [[mermaid]]s.{{Cite dragon/425/Spin a Yarn: The Night Thelva Clovenaxe Flew|43}}
